<p style="text-align:justify;">1806 July.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">to be more at our ease and fare better.  Accordingly M<sup>r</sup> Chaboillez and his people took the lodgings with the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Ha<span class="DelHand-author">r</span>iry horn</span> &#8212; our guide went with the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">straight Horn</span> and I with my people remained with <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Le Grand</span> this Indian I found Extremely civil, he gave me up his own bed, which was comfortable being <span class="AddHand-author">elevated</span> from the ground and surrounded with dressed skins.  We had a plentiful supply of corn and beans.  Soon after accepting of invitations to other huts we Experienced my kindness and were treated with berries and parched corn pounded together which we thought a good Dish<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  But on such occasions it is expected that you will give something to the master in return for his civilities<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[W]</span>e paid a visit to the Grand Blanc who notwithstanding our Slight in declining his invitation had still his flag displayed in honor of our arrival<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  We made him a small present to make amends for the offence<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[W]</span>e fond Old Jaussaume a Canadian who had been for fifteen Years resident among the Mandanes in this Village<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  He speakes the language tolerably has a wife and family who dress as the natives.  As for himself he still retains the outward appearance of a</p>
<p style="text-align:right;"><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Christian</span>-</p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[24]</span></p>

